replies.bodyText:
Actually desireActiveTaskCount usually can't be equal to currentActiveTaskCount here. Take scale out as an example :
Here is the logic of computing desireActiveTaskCount in autoscaler
      if (currentActiveTaskCount == defaultAutoScalerConfig.getTaskCountMax()) {
        log.info("CurrentActiveTaskCount reach task count Max limit, skip to scale out tasks for dataSource [%s].", dataSource);
        return -1;
      } else {
        desiredActiveTaskCount = Math.min(taskCount, defaultAutoScalerConfig.getTaskCountMax());
      }

Condition 1: int taskCount = currentActiveTaskCount + defaultAutoScalerConfig.getScaleOutStep()
Condition 2: currentActiveTaskCount != defaultAutoScalerConfig.getTaskCountMax() otherwise will return -1.
Condition 3: desiredActiveTaskCount = Math.min(taskCount, defaultAutoScalerConfig.getTaskCountMax())
Condition 4: defaultAutoScalerConfig.getScaleOutStep() > 0
=>  get Condition5 based on Condition 1 and Condition 3: desiredActiveTaskCount = Math.min(currentActiveTaskCount + defaultAutoScalerConfig.getScaleOutStep(), defaultAutoScalerConfig.getTaskCountMax())
Assume desireActiveTaskCount == currentActiveTaskCount
Combine with Condition 4, 5 and assumption => we can get desiredActiveTaskCount == defaultAutoScalerConfig.getTaskCountMax()
Then based on Condition 2 => We can get currentActiveTaskCount != desiredActiveTaskCount
This conclusion conflicts with the assumption, so the assumption does not hold.
So that desireActiveTaskCount can't be equal to currentActiveTaskCount here
UNLESS! Users set defaultAutoScalerConfig.getScaleOutStep() = 0 by mistake.
So I changed the code as you suggested to avoid this scenario.
Thanks for your suggestion!

